<DOC><DOCNO> AP890522-0098 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-22-89 1427EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w BC-ScotusAt-a-Glance     05-22 0542</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Scotus At-a-Glance,530</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Here, at a glance, are highlights of actionstaken Monday by the Supreme Court.      UNIFICATION CHURCH      The court refused to shield the Rev. Sun Myung Moon'sUnification Church from being sued by two former members who saythey were duped into joining it.   The court, without comment, rejected arguments that religiousfreedom protects the church against allegations of ``brainwashing''and fraudulent recruiting.   The case is Holy Spirit Association vs. Molko, 88-1600.      JOHN WAYNE GACY      The court turned down an appeal by mass murderer John WayneGacy, convicted and sentenced to death in 1980 for killing 33 boysand young men.   The justices rejected arguments that Illinois' death penalty lawwrongly gives county prosecutors ``complete and unguided discretionto determine whether to seek the death penalty in murder cases.''   Gacy's appeal also had contended that he was denied a fair trialbecause the presiding judge limited the testimony of an expertpsychiatric witness for the defense.   The case is Gacy vs. Illinois, 88-6828.      EVIDENCE      The court l Limited federal judges' power to exclude potentiallyprejudicial evidence from civil trials, ruling against a youngPennsylvania man who lost his arm in a car wash accident.   The justices, by a 6-3 vote, said Paul Green's product-liabilitylawsuit was not denied a fair trial when lawyers representing thesued manufacturer were allowed to tell jurors about Green'scriminal record.   The case is Green vs. Bock Laundry Machine Co., 87-1816.      SOCIAL SECURITY      The court agreed to study a federal regulation aimed at savingthe government time and money when it mistakenly overpays someSocial Security recipients.   The court said it will study a ruling in a Colorado case thatstruck down the regulation.   The case is Sullivan vs. Everhart, 88-1323.      AIRPORT NOISE      The court refused to shield Chicago from being sued for monetarydamages in state court for allegedly allowing excessive noise andair pollution at O'Hare International Airport.   The justices, without comment, let stand a ruling that the courtallow such lawsuits.   The cases are Chicago vs. Beineman, 88-1496; Bieneman vs.Chicago, 88-1497; and American Airlines vs. Chicago, 88-1670.      FRAUD      The court rejected an appeal by a former Chicago councilmanconvicted of fraud for illegally conspiring to buy and selltax-delinquent properties.   The court, over one dissenting vote, refused to use the case ofThomas E. Keane to set guidelines on when some people may challengetheir fraud convictions after completing prison terms for thoseconvictions.   The case is Keane vs. U.S., 88-1178.      ACHILLE LAURO      The court ruled that a lawsuit stemming from the terroristhijacking of the cruise ship Achille Lauro in 1985 may be tried ina federal court in New York City.   Voting 9-0, the justices rejected an appeal by the ship ownersaimed at transferring the suit to a court in Naples, Italy.   The case is Lauro Lines vs. Chasser, 88-23.      PRISONER      The court made deadlines for the filing of civil rights lawsuitsby some prison inmates more flexible.   The court unanimously ruled in a case from Michigan that statesmay give prisoners extra leeway on when they file such federalsuits.   The case is Hardin vs. Straub, 87-7023.</TEXT></DOC>